A Retrospective Review
Michael F. Dombek, DPM,1 Bradley M. Lamm, DPM,2 Karl Saltrick, DPM, FACFAS,3 Robert W. Mendicino, DPM, FACFAS,4 and Alan R. Catanzariti, DPM, FACFAS5

A Retrospective Review
Tears of the peroneal tendons are not uncommon but remain an underappreciated source of chronic lateral ankle pain.
The purpose of this study was to identify the typical patient proﬁle and nature of the injury, to analyze the course of treatment, and to determine the prevalence of complications seen with surgical repair.
Forty patients with chronic pain over the peroneal tendons from the Foot and Ankle Institute at the Western Pennsylvania Hospital underwent peroneal tendon repair.
During a 3-year period, a retrospective review was performed by evaluating medical records, surgical reports, and radiographs.
The average patient age was 42 years (range, 13 to 64 years).
The most common cause was an ankle sprain or other traumatic injury (58%).
Peroneus brevis tears (35 patients; 88%), peroneus longus tears (5 patients; 13%), combined peroneus brevis and longus tears (15 patients; 37%), low-lying peroneus muscle belly (13 patients; 33%), lateral ankle ligamentous disruptions (13 patients; 33%), and peroneal subluxation (8 patients; 20%) were identiﬁed during surgery.
The average follow-up was 13 months (range, 9 to 40 months).
Ninety-eight percent of the patients were able to return to full activities without pain at ﬁnal follow-up.
The minor complication rate (transient symptoms) was 20%.
Clinically signiﬁcant (major) complications (continued symptoms or revisionary surgery) occurred in 10% of patients.
This study indicates that lateral ankle ligamentous incompetence, combined peroneal brevis and longus tears, and low-lying peroneus muscle belly commonly coexist in patients with peroneal tendon injuries.
Appropriate surgical intervention of peroneal tendon tears and their coexisting pathology yields successful and predictable results with few clinically signiﬁcant complications.
(The Journal of Foot & Ankle Surgery 42(5):250–258, 2003) Key words: peroneus brevis tears, peroneus longus tears, l l ankle injury atera

A Retrospective Review > Arthur
William Meyer, a human anatomist, was the ﬁrst to observe longitudinal peroneus brevis tears in both a Spanish sailor and an Irish dishwasher.
Interestingly, Meyer in the human body, lack a gross reparative process.
Since this discovery, there have been few studies that explore the full clinical spectrum of peroneus brevis and longus tendon tears.
Peroneal tendon tears are frequently overlooked because of the vague nature of pain along the lateral ankle region.
These tears have been reported to occur after an acute traumatic event or without any identiﬁable traumatic episode (2).
Warmth, edema, and tenderness along the course of the peroneal tendons in the ﬁbular groove are the common physical ﬁndings (2,3).
Manual muscle strength testing may show little or no weakness of the peroneal tendons, which further complicates the diagnosis (2).

Multiple mechanisms of injury have been implicated in peroneal tendon tears, such as acute inversion ankle sprains, chronic ankle ligamentous laxity, and peroneal subluxation (2,3).
In addition, several authors have documented that pre- disposing anatomic factors may also contribute to these tendon tears.
A convex or ﬂat ﬁbular groove, low-lying or anomalous muscle belly, superior peroneal retinaculum incompetence, posterior lateral ﬁbular spurring, and a high-arch foot type have all been directly associated with peroneal tendon injury (1,3– 5).
Magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) studies have also showed that anatomic factors, both osseous and soft tissue, contribute to peroneal tendon injury (6–9).

Previous research evaluating peroneal tendon pathology has been focused on either isolated brevis or longus tendon tears, or on a speciﬁc anatomic structure that predisposes these tendons to injury (3,4,6–9).
Several clinical studies have explored the relationship between lateral ankle instability and peroneal tendon tears (5,10–12).
However, no study has attempted to analyze the entire lateral ankle complex as a whole, whereby the interrelationships of peroneus longus tears, peroneus brevis tears, predisposing anatomic factors, and lateral ankle ligamentous incompetence are studied.
The purpose of this study was to identify the typical patient proﬁle, discover the mechanism of injury, analyze the course of treatment, and determine the prevalence of those minor and clinically relevant complications seen with surgical repair of the peroneal tendons.

A Retrospective Review > Materials and Methods
Forty patients from the Foot and Ankle Institute of Western Pennsylvania at the Western Pennsylvania Hospital (Pittsburgh, PA) who underwent a surgical repair of a peroneal tendon tear were reviewed.
All of these patients underwent surgical repair because of longstanding symptoms associated with a peroneus brevis and/or longus tendon injury.
Four individual surgeons performed the surgeries during a 3-year period.
A retrospective review was performed to obtain objective data from patient records, surgical reports, and multiplanar radiographs (anteroposterior, lateral, and axial).

The following angles were measured: calcaneal inclination, talar declination, anatomic anterior distal tibial angle (aADTA), talo-ﬁrst metatarsal angle (for both the sagittal and the transverse planes), mid-diaphyseal line of the tibia to the calcaneal bisection line, anatomic lateral distal tibial angle, and talocalcaneal angle (Figs. 1–3) (13,14).
These multiplanar radiographic angles were determined with an X-Caliper digital-measuring device (Eisenlohr Technologies Inc, Davis, CA).
The mean angular measurements for each radiographic parameter were calculated to examine the foot architecture in patients with peroneal tendon tears.

A Retrospective Review > Materials and Methods > Clinical Evaluation
A comprehensive chart review was performed to compile each patient’s age, sex, surgical history, mechanism of injury, presentation of symptoms, physical examination ﬁndings, and concurrent injuries.
In addition, the length and number of conservative treatments, time until diagnosis, initial diagnosis, number of diagnoses, number of physicians seen before diagnosis, preoperative radiographic ﬁndings, and advanced imaging techniques were collected.
The length of follow-up, number and type of complications, surgical ﬁndings, and activity level at last follow-up were also recorded.

Complications were categorized as minor or clinically relevant (major).
Minor complications were deﬁned as transient postoperative symptomatology that resolved with nonsurgical treatment.
The clinically relevant (major) complications were deﬁned as continued postoperative symptoms, which were recalcitrant to nonsurgical treatment or that required revisionary surgery.
At the ﬁnal follow-up, it was determined if patients had returned to full activity with or without pain.

A Retrospective Review > Materials and Methods > Surgical Technique
During surgical exploration, the peroneal tendons were carefully inspected.
Special attention was paid to the ante- rior or deep aspect of the peroneus brevis tendon, which is in contact with the ﬁbula, where longitudinal tears are commonly found (2,10,15).
A low-lying peroneus brevis Surgical exploration of the lateral collateral ligaments was performed when preoperative clinical and/or radio- graphic instability testing was positive.
Intraoperatively, a subjective functional assessment of the lateral collateral ligaments (anterior drawer/talar tilt) was reevaluated and the lateral collateral ligaments were inspected.
When the insta- bility tests were positive and the surgical inspection of the ligaments showed incompetence, a modiﬁed Broström- Gould repair was performed (16).
The peroneal tendon subluxation was also objectively evaluated intraoperatively.
Subluxation was addressed by reeﬁng of the superior pero- neal retinaculum in a pants-over-vest fashion along with a groove-deepening procedure if the retroﬁbular groove was ﬂat or convex (17).
Coexisting pathology (talar osteochon- dral lesions, fracture fragments, and so on) was also re- paired at the time of surgery.
The repaired peroneal tendons were then replaced in anatomic position, and the superior peroneal retinaculum was imbricated and repaired to prevent future subluxation (2).

A Retrospective Review > Materials and Methods > Surgical Technique
The postoperative care for a peroneal tendon repair typically included a compression dressing and a posterior splint for the immediate postoperative period (3 to 7 days).
A non-weightbearing below-the-knee cast is applied in neutral ankle position for 3 to 4 weeks, followed by a 2- to 3-week period of protected weightbearing in a walking brace.
Physical therapy and range-of-motion exercises were initiated by the fourth to eighth postoperative week, depending on each patient’s clinical ﬁndings.

A Retrospective Review > Results > Clinical Results
Peroneal (peroneus brevis and/or longus) tendon repair was performed on 30 female and 10 male patients, with an average age of 42 years (range, 13 to 64 years).
Twentythree (58%) patients recalled a history of a traumatic injury, whereas 17 patients (42%) could not recall any speciﬁc event.
Various mechanisms of injury were reported, all of which had an insidious onset of lateral ankle symptoms: ankle sprains (14 patients; 61%), ankle fractures (2 patients), work-related injuries (2 patients), injury from a fall (2 patients), ﬁfth metatarsal fracture (1 patient), motorvehicle accident (1 patient), and a blunt injury (1 patient).

A Retrospective Review > Results > Clinical Results
Past medical history was remarkable in only 2 patients; 1 patient had rheumatoid arthritis and 1 had psoriatic arthritis.

A Retrospective Review > Results > Clinical Results
The average length of time of nonsurgical treatment was 25.7 weeks (range, 0 to 156 weeks) before initial presentation to the authors at the Foot and Ankle Institute at the Western Pennsylvania Hospital.
Thirty-six of 40 patients underwent an unsuccessful course of nonsurgical treatment modalities that included anti-inﬂammatory medications, ankle bracing, cast immobilization, physical therapy, change in shoe gear/orthotics, rest/decrease in activity, and intratendinous-sheath steroid injections.
Each patient in this study underwent an average number of 2.2 nonsurgical treatment modalities that failed before surgical intervention (range, 0 to 6).

Twenty-eight (70%) patients had been treated by at least 1 other physician before referral to our institution.
In addition, each patient was seen by an average of 2 physicians before diagnosis of a peroneal tendon tear (range, 1 to 4).
There was an average of 3.3 different diagnoses per patient before MRI or surgical conﬁrmation (range, 1 to 7).
The average length of time from the initial visit at our institution until conﬁrmation of a peroneal injury (via surgery or MRI) was 7.3 weeks (range, 0 to 80 weeks).

Twenty-one patients (53%) presented with isolated lateral ankle pain or as part of their chief complaints.
Other complaints included difﬁculty with walking or exertional activity (45%), recent ankle sprain (20%), swelling (15%), lateral ankle instability/history of multiple ankle sprains (8%), chronic pain (5%), and clicking near the region of the peroneal tendons (5%).
During the initial physical examination at our institution, the clinical ﬁndings were pain on palpation to the peroneal tendons in 30 patients (75%), edema/warmth in 24 patients (60%), pain with eversion/ inversion in 13 patients (33%), antalgic gait in 11 patients (28%), pain on palpation to the lateral collateral ligament(s) in 9 patients (23%), and muscle weakness in 4 patients (10%).

A Retrospective Review > Results > Radiologic Results
All patients in this study had foot and ankle radiographs.
However, some radiographs (19 patients) were unavailable for angular measurements because of the non-weightbearing nature of emergency room ﬁlms.
Preoperative radiographic ﬁndings included 2 avulsion fractures of the ﬁbula, 2 os vesalianum, 1 os peroneum, 1 ﬁfth metatarsal fracture, 1 Stieda process fracture, and 1 enlarged peroneal tubercle.

A Retrospective Review > Results > Radiologic Results
Thirty-eight patients had a preoperative MRI performed.
Three patients underwent a mechanical ankle stress examination (anterior drawer/talar tilt) of which 2 patients showed lateral ankle instability.
Two patients had a bone scan performed, identifying 1 with a stress fracture of the ﬁfth metatarsal base.

A Retrospective Review > Results > Radiologic Results > Surgical Results
Thirty-ﬁve (88%) patients underwent repair of the peroneus brevis tendon.
Thirteen had a debridement performed, 18 had a debridement and tubularization, and 4 had a debridement and tenodesis to the longus tendon (2 patients had complete ruptures) (Fig. 6).
Fifteen (37%) patients who had a peroneus brevis tear were found to have an associated peroneus longus injury.

A Retrospective Review > Results > Radiologic Results > Surgical Results
Eighteen (45%) patients underwent surgical repair of the peroneus longus tendon, whereas 5 (13%) patients had isolated peroneus longus tendon repair.
Eleven had a de- bridement, 6 had debridement and tubularization, and 1 had debridement and tenodesis to the brevis tendon because of a complete rupture.
One of these patients had an ostectomy of a hypertrophied peroneal tubercle, which was considered part of the cause of the peroneus longus tear.
One patient had an excision of a painful os peroneum.

A Retrospective Review > Results > Radiologic Results > Surgical Results
FIGURE 7 A low-lying peroneus brevis muscle belly (A), causing encroachment.

A Retrospective Review > Results > Radiologic Results > Surgical Results
Eight (20%) patients showed peroneal tendon subluxation intraoperatively.
All patients had a direct repair of the superior peroneal retinaculum, whereas 4 (10%) patients underwent groove-deepening procedures for a ﬂattened or convex ﬁbular groove.
In conjunction with a peroneal tendon repair, thirteen (33%) patients had a resection of a low-lying peroneus brevis muscle belly to decompress the ﬁbular groove, whereas 13 (33%) patients underwent a lateral ankle stabilization procedure (Fig. 7).
In addition to a peroneal tendon repair, 10 concomitant procedures were performed: excision of fracture fragments (3 patients), removal of ganglion cysts (2 patients), repair of talar dome lesions (2 patients), resection of an enlarged Stieda process (1 patient), neurectomy (1 patient), and repair of a chronic Achilles tendon tear (1 patient).
The average number of concomitant procedures was 2.6 per patient.

A Retrospective Review > Results > Radiologic Results > Outcomes
The patients were followed-up postoperatively for an average of 13 months (range, 9 to 40 months).
Complications were subdivided into 2 groups: minor and clinically relevant (major) complications.
Eight (20%) patients had minor complications, which included transient sural neuritis (5 patients), tendonitis symptoms that resolved with activity (2 patients), and asymptomatic peroneal subluxation (1 patient).
Four patients (10%) had a clinically relevant (major) complication.
These major complications included: hematoma (1 patient), wound dehiscence (1 patient), unresolved symptoms of tendonitis with activity (1 patient), and an unstable ankle (1 patient).
At the ﬁnal follow-up, only 1 of 40 patients had pain with full activity and was considered an unsuccessful result.

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
In the largest retrospective study of its kind, this study evaluated 40 patients with a surgically conﬁrmed peroneus brevis and/or longus tendon tear.
Fifty-eight percent of patients with a peroneal tendon tear had a history of injury, whereas 42% of the patients denied any traumatic history.
The most common precipitating traumatic event was an ankle sprain (61%).
Krause et al (3) found similar results: 55% of their patient population had a traumatic event and 45% had an unknown cause of the peroneus brevis tears.
Several studies have shown that peroneal tendon injuries are invariably resistant to nonsurgical therapy and surgical intervention is often required (17–19).
Similarly, all 40 patients in this series had no relief of symptoms with nonsurgical treatment even with an extensive period of conservative care.

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
Fifty-three percent of our patients presented with a chief complaint of lateral ankle pain, and 45% had pain with activity and difﬁculty walking.
The majority of patients had pain on palpation of the peroneal tendons (75%) and edema/ warmth (60%) during clinical examination.
Pain with eversion/inversion was found to occur in a lower percentage of our patients than might be expected (33%), which is synchronous with the ﬁndings of Krause and Brodsky (3).
It appears that the most consistent preoperative clinical ﬁndings after peroneal tendon injuries are edema and tenderness in the lateral ankle (3).

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
Many authors report peroneal tendon injuries as a frequently overlooked clinical entity (3,19,20).
Only 60% of the peroneal tendon injuries in this study were accurately diagnosed on the initial ofﬁce visit.
Most of the patients incurring trauma are screened by health providers who are unfamiliar with these types of injuries.
Moreover, the average number of diagnoses per patient was 3.3 before presentation to the authors.
These patients were seen by an average of 2 other physicians before the establishment of the deﬁnitive diagnosis.
This suggests that a large percentage of peroneal tendon injuries are initially misdiagnosed by a wide variety of healthcare providers.

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
The mean calcaneal inclination and aADTA were increased, indicating a supinated foot type.
The increased aADTA is evidence of a procurvatum ankle architecture, in which the distal articular surface of the tibia is angulated to face posteriorly (Fig. 8).
The mean calcaneal position was 4.1° varus, which is also consistent with a cavovarus hindfoot posture.
In 1 study, 82% of patients with peroneal tendon injuries had an associated supinated foot type (4)

A Retrospective Review > Discussion

The authors believe that a cavovarus foot structure along with the ﬁnding of a procurvatum ankle may be the foot type that is predisposed to peroneal tendon injury.

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
Although the diagnosis of a peroneal injury is typically attained through a comprehensive history and physical examination, an MRI may be invaluable.
MRI is useful in visualizing tendon tears and other predisposing anatomic factors.
Several studies have shown that an MRI is helpful for preoperative surgical planning (6-8).
In our study, 95% of the patients had a preoperative MRI performed.
Although we did not report the correlation of the MRI results to the surgical ﬁndings, we found these studies to be useful in our overall approach to these patients.
Therefore, with failure of nonsurgical treatment and a high index of suspicion, an MRI should lead to the appropriate diagnosis.

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
Some authors maintain that the subluxation of the peroneal tendons over the posterolateral edge of the ﬁbula plays a crucial role in the development of peroneal brevis injuries (2,3,21–23).
In 1 study, 19 of 20 patients (95%) showed peroneal tendon subluxation intraoperatively (3).
Our results showed a lower percentage of intraoperative subluxation (20%).
Because of the subjective nature of this ﬁnding, the authors believe this entity is difﬁcult to quantify.

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
Our opinion is that an intraoperative assessment of the lateral collateral ligaments should be performed (11).
The relationship of peroneus brevis tears with lateral ankle instability has been well documented (5,10–12).
Sammarco et al (10) reported 12 of 47 patients (26%) with injured peroneal tendons also underwent concomitant lateral ankle stabilization procedures.
Thirty-three percent of the patients in this study also had a lateral ankle stabilization procedure performed.
The authors anticipated this ﬁnding secondary to the high number of associated ankle sprains.

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
The presence of an anomalous low-lying peroneus brevis muscle belly, a peroneus quartus tendon, or a biﬁd peroneus brevis can cause an overcrowding phenomenon in the ret- roﬁbular region and has been implicated in the creation of peroneal tendon tears (9).
Pathologic conditions such as peroneal tenosynovitis and hypertrophy can also contribute to or are a result of this phenomenon (22).
Surgical excision or debulking of these accessory muscles is recommended to decompress the ﬁbular groove (22).
MRI and cadaveric studies have shown a 10% to 21.7% prevalence of a peroneus quartus tendon (9,24,25).
Although no peroneus quartus tendons were identiﬁed in this study, this anomalous tendon can cause a peroneal tendon tear (Fig. 4).
However, 33% of the patients showed a low-lying peroneus brevis muscle belly, which is the highest association ever reported (9,24,25).
All accessory peroneal musculature (including peroneus quartus tendons) was categorized into a low-lying peroneus muscle belly group because of the variations in lateral peroneal accessory muscles.

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
Studies have found that the presence of a sharp posterior ﬁbular ridge contributes to the splitting of the brevis tendon (18,21–23).
When the contour of the ﬁbula is recognized as an etiologic factor, the sharpened edge should be resected (2).
Groove-deepening procedures have also been used to address the abnormal retroﬁbular anatomy.
Advocates of this procedure suggest that this eliminates structural predisposing factors (17).
In our study, 4 (10%) patients had a groove-deepening procedure performed.

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
Peroneus longus tears typically occur in 3 distinct anatomic zones: the lateral malleolus, the peroneal tubercle/ trochlear process of the calcaneus, and the cuboid notch (4,20).
The authors found 5 isolated peroneus longus injuries in this series.
A combined peroneus longus and brevis tendon injury was noted in 37% of our patients.
Similarly, Brandes et al (4) discovered a 33% association of peroneus brevis tears with peroneus longus tears.
This suggests that Eight patients (20%) had minor complications.
There were 5 patients who developed transient sural neuritis, 2 patients had residual tendonitis with activity, and 1 patient had an asymptomatic peroneal subluxation postoperatively.
All minor complications resolved uneventfully or did not alter restoration of function.

A Retrospective Review > Discussion
Because of the retrospective nature of this study, limitations include the lack of a subjective patient questionnaire, preoperative multiplanar radiographs and dynamic lateral ankle instability testing for all patients, and surgical notation of location of peroneal tears.
Future studies should include a surgical correlation to MRI ﬁndings and a pre- and postoperative postural and gait analysis to determine the validity of MRI and the functional outcome of these peroneal tendon repairs.

A Retrospective Review > Conclusion
Physical signs such as tenderness on palpation in the ﬁbular groove, edema along the tendon sheath, and subluxation are diagnostic of peroneal tendon pathology.
These injuries are frequently overlooked and misdiagnosed because of the vague nature of symptoms.
In addition, lateral ankle ligamentous injuries commonly coexist in these patients.
The mechanisms of these injuries are not completely understood.
However, the authors believe that peroneal tendon injuries are not independent of each other and cannot be separated from other predisposing soft-tissue and osseous anatomic structures around the entire lateral complex.
Although nonsurgical measures are usually attempted, surgical repair of peroneal tears is usually indicated.
Successful results can be expected with proper patient selection, evaluation, and treatment.
